al presence defined the boundaries of the “Free World” and elevated the United States as the central actor in Cold War geopolitics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCold War. 0aPresidents-United States-Influence. 0aRhetoric-Political aspects-United States-History-20th century. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh  aUS presidential rhetoric, US foreign policy, global rhetorical presidency, Cold War, Harry S. Truman, Dwight D. Eisenhower, John F. Kennedy, Richard Nixon, Ronald Reagan.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2023 Englishz978311131916208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2023z9783111318240oZDB-23-DSP08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226823645423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226823645/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-131916-2  EBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishb2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2023  aZDB-23-DSPb2023